1
00:00:00,200 --> 00:00:05,960
In this video, we are going to learn opening sessions in Martin as a document database.

2
00:00:06,260 --> 00:00:12,860
Martin's session is an interaction pattern for working with the documents stored in PostgreSQL database.

3
00:00:13,160 --> 00:00:15,200
You can see the image on the slide.

4
00:00:15,200 --> 00:00:21,800
I document store is the root of the Martin usage, but most of the Martin usage in the code will start

5
00:00:21,800 --> 00:00:26,930
with one of these session types that can be created from an I document store.

6
00:00:27,200 --> 00:00:32,930
So under the I document store there are different flavors of session and the root store.

7
00:00:33,020 --> 00:00:41,180
So these are the query sessions that optimize for read only scenarios and document sessions that optimize

8
00:00:41,180 --> 00:00:43,160
for the read and write scenarios.

9
00:00:43,190 --> 00:00:45,290
So let me explain one by one.

10
00:00:45,470 --> 00:00:47,810
The first one is query sessions.

11
00:00:47,840 --> 00:00:54,680
These sessions is best used for querying documents without any need for the tracking or saving changes.

12
00:00:55,070 --> 00:01:02,600
So under the document session for read and write operation, we can also use different type of the document

13
00:01:02,600 --> 00:01:03,260
sessions.

14
00:01:03,290 --> 00:01:07,610
Let me start the first one which is the identity map documentation.

15
00:01:07,610 --> 00:01:14,030
Martin's I document session implement the identity map pattern that seeks to cache documents loaded

16
00:01:14,030 --> 00:01:14,780
by ID.

17
00:01:14,930 --> 00:01:21,590
This behavior can be very valuable, for example, in handling the web requests or service bus messages.

18
00:01:21,590 --> 00:01:26,690
When many different objects or functions may need to access the same logical document.

19
00:01:27,320 --> 00:01:30,230
The second type is lightweight document session.

20
00:01:30,230 --> 00:01:35,690
It is suitable for small transactions with a mix of the read and write operations.

21
00:01:35,690 --> 00:01:41,720
For operations that involve updates, inserts or deletes, we use a lightweight sessions.

22
00:01:41,720 --> 00:01:46,640
It is still transactional but doesn't track the changes to the loaded document.

23
00:01:47,240 --> 00:01:50,900
And the last one is dirty checking documentation.

24
00:01:50,900 --> 00:01:57,530
This is the dirty checking document session in this case, and I document station opened with a dirty

25
00:01:57,530 --> 00:01:58,670
checking enabled.

26
00:01:58,670 --> 00:02:04,610
The session will try to detect the changes to any of the documents loaded by that session.

27
00:02:04,610 --> 00:02:11,030
The dirty checking is done by keeping the original Json fetched from the PostgreSQL, and using the

28
00:02:11,030 --> 00:02:15,410
Newtonsoft.json library that makes a node by node.

29
00:02:15,410 --> 00:02:21,620
Comparison of the Json representation of the document at the time that I document session is called,

30
00:02:21,620 --> 00:02:23,420
so you can find the image.

31
00:02:23,420 --> 00:02:27,530
How we can create these kind of sessions from the Martin Document DB.

32
00:02:27,650 --> 00:02:34,100
And here you can see that we can use a document store and dot notation to create query session.

33
00:02:34,100 --> 00:02:39,860
Here you can see the query session and we can create lightweight sessions, identity sessions, dirty

34
00:02:39,860 --> 00:02:41,480
tricks sessions and so on.

35
00:02:41,480 --> 00:02:45,410
These provide to create sessions using the document store.

36
00:02:45,410 --> 00:02:52,430
And here you can see the operations to perform read write operations or enable to identity map and dirty

37
00:02:52,430 --> 00:02:53,960
checking functions.

38
00:02:54,470 --> 00:02:56,060
So what is the best practice?

39
00:02:56,060 --> 00:03:01,760
Best practice is understanding and choosing the right type of the session in Martin, which is crucial

40
00:03:01,760 --> 00:03:04,520
for effective data handling in your applications.

41
00:03:04,520 --> 00:03:11,420
Always aim to use the lightest session that meets your needs and ensure proper disposal of the sessions

42
00:03:11,420 --> 00:03:13,460
in order to maintain the performance.

43
00:03:13,460 --> 00:03:20,300
So we will use mostly lightweight session which is optimized for reading and writing operations.

